  "text": "By solving (33), we pick parameters k 1 = 1.7896, k 2 = 2.2278, ℓ 1 = 0.0538, ℓ 2 = −1.1633. It can be verified that the eigenvalue ofÃ according to this set of parameters are −2.5087 ± 0.1208i. Moreover, µ(Ã) = −1.9123. With initial conditions x(0) = 3, x 1 (0) = x 2 (0) = x 0 (0) = 5, a simulation for m(t) ≡ 0.3 is shown in Figure 5 . It is worth to note that there is an improvement of the steady-state error by the proposed observer, e ⋆ = 0.2272, while the Luenberger observer gives e ⋆ 0 = 0.2400. As shown in Figure 5 (b), we obtain t ⋆ = 2s, and e becomes closer to 0 than e 0 thereafter. Based on Theorem 3.9, we are able to find better parameters by using the solver PENBMI [CITATION_1] . For values k 1 ≈ 3.5198, k 2 ≈ 0.4802, ℓ 1 ≈ −8.0142, ℓ 2 ≈ 0.2883, the resulting H ∞ gain is ≈ 0.4953, which is ≈ 38.09% smaller than that of Luenberger observer (γ 0 = 0.8) with k 0 = 2. The simulation in Figure 2 was obtained using these parameters.",
